<subSubSection lastPageId="28" lastPageNumber="29" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1437,253,2037]" lastBlockId="28.[151,1436,151,392]" lastPageId="28" lastPageNumber="29" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1940,1965]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Comments.</emphasis>
The head of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lindner &amp; Ferrari &amp; Mound &amp; Cavalleri" authorityYear="2018" box="[488,621,1940,1965]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cardosoi">
<emphasis box="[488,621,1940,1965]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">H. cardosoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characteristic in being longer than wide and having maxillary stylets very close medially, touching each other in some specimens (
<figureCitation box="[878,966,1976,2001]" captionStart="FIGURES 45–50" captionStartId="28.[151,264,1970,1993]" captionTargetBox="[168,1409,455,1948]" captionTargetId="figure@28.[159,1409,455,1948]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURES 45–50. Holopothrips cardosoi sp. nov. holotype and paratypes. (45) body; (46) head and pronotum; (47) metanotal sculpture; (48) pore plates on abdominal sternites VII–VIII; (49) spermatheca; (50) pelta." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1445198/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Fig. 46</figureCitation>
), a trait that is shared with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Costa Lima" authorityYear="1935" box="[1301,1429,1977,2000]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ananasi">
<emphasis box="[1301,1429,1977,2000]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">H. ananasi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lindner &amp; Ferrari &amp; Mound &amp; Cavalleri" authorityYear="2018" box="[266,397,2012,2037]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cardosoi">
<emphasis box="[266,397,2012,2037]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">H. cardosoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
lacks the characteristic sculpture formed by small equiangular reticles that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Costa Lima" authorityYear="1935" box="[1240,1364,2013,2037]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ananasi">
<emphasis box="[1240,1364,2013,2037]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">H. ananasi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has in the head and metanotum, and has the antennal segments shorter and more robust. Another remarkable trait of this species is the lack of anteroangular pore plates in males, bearing only the posterior transverse band on sternites VII–VIII (
<figureCitation box="[269,356,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURES 45–50" captionStartId="28.[151,264,1970,1993]" captionTargetBox="[168,1409,455,1948]" captionTargetId="figure@28.[159,1409,455,1948]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURES 45–50. Holopothrips cardosoi sp. nov. holotype and paratypes. (45) body; (46) head and pronotum; (47) metanotal sculpture; (48) pore plates on abdominal sternites VII–VIII; (49) spermatheca; (50) pelta." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1445198/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig. 48</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lindner &amp; Ferrari &amp; Mound &amp; Cavalleri" authorityYear="2018" box="[378,633,223,248]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cardosoi">
<emphasis box="[378,633,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Holopothrips cardosoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be related to some other large, dark-bodied species of the genus with two pairs of epimeral setae, such as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lindner &amp; Ferrari &amp; Mound &amp; Cavalleri" authorityYear="2018" box="[607,751,260,285]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="atlanticus">
<emphasis box="[607,751,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">H. atlanticus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Lindner &amp; Ferrari &amp; Mound &amp; Cavalleri, 2018" authorityName="Lindner &amp; Ferrari &amp; Mound &amp; Cavalleri" authorityYear="2018" box="[804,943,261,284]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigrisetis" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[804,943,261,284]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">H. nigrisetis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[949,1012,260,285]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[949,1012,260,285]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">sp. n.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
(both with V-shaped maxillary stylets instead of parallel, and three pore plates on sternite VIII instead of one), and 
<taxonomicName authority="Lindner &amp; Ferrari &amp; Mound &amp; Cavalleri, 2018" authorityName="Lindner &amp; Ferrari &amp; Mound &amp; Cavalleri" authorityYear="2018" box="[1028,1145,297,320]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigrum" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[1028,1145,297,320]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">H. nigrum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1153,1217,295,320]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1153,1217,295,320]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">sp. n.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
(which has closely striate metanotal sculpture instead of reticles). This species induces terminal rosette galls on an undetermined 
<emphasis box="[151,231,369,392]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Myrcia</emphasis>
species (
<figureCitation box="[334,401,367,392]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–9" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1630,1653]" captionTargetBox="[234,1352,184,1606]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[234,1352,183,1606]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–9. Leaf-galls induced by Holopothrips (white arrows). (1) galls on Siphoneugena reitzii (by H. curiosus); (2) galls on Myrciaria floribunda (by H. spermathecus) (Photo: André Santana); (3) gall on Myrcia guianensis (by H. molzi); (4) gall on Myrcia retorta (by H. striatus); (5) gall on Myrcia sp. (by H. cardosoi) (Photo: João C. Cardoso); (6) gall on Myrcia splendens (by H. conducans); (7) gall on Myrcia splendens (by H. longisetus); (8) gall on Myrcia selloi (by H. acrioris); (9) galls on Neomitranthes obscura (by H. varicolor) (Photo: Sheila Carvalho-Fernandes)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1445184/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
), very similar in structure to that induced by 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Priesner" authorityYear="1921" box="[907,1061,367,392]" class="Insecta" family="Thysanoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Phrasterothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="conducans">
<emphasis box="[907,1061,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">H. conducans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<taxonomicName box="[1097,1244,367,392]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Miconia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Magnoliopsida" rank="species" species="splendens">
<emphasis box="[1097,1244,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">M. splendens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1260,1328,367,392]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–9" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1630,1653]" captionTargetBox="[234,1352,184,1606]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[234,1352,183,1606]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–9. Leaf-galls induced by Holopothrips (white arrows). (1) galls on Siphoneugena reitzii (by H. curiosus); (2) galls on Myrciaria floribunda (by H. spermathecus) (Photo: André Santana); (3) gall on Myrcia guianensis (by H. molzi); (4) gall on Myrcia retorta (by H. striatus); (5) gall on Myrcia sp. (by H. cardosoi) (Photo: João C. Cardoso); (6) gall on Myrcia splendens (by H. conducans); (7) gall on Myrcia splendens (by H. longisetus); (8) gall on Myrcia selloi (by H. acrioris); (9) galls on Neomitranthes obscura (by H. varicolor) (Photo: Sheila Carvalho-Fernandes)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1445184/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
